{{outline|Outline of the metric system}}
The '''metre–tonne–second''' or '''MTS''' system of units is a system of [[physical unit]]s. It was invented in France, hence the unit names ''sthène'' and ''pièze'', and became its legal system between 1919 and 1961 ("décret" 5 May 1961, "Journal Officiel"). It was adopted by the [[Soviet Union]] in 1933 and abolished there in 1955. It was a [[metric system|metric]] and [[coherent system]] of units, much as [[SI]] and the [[centimetre–gram–second system]] (CGS), but with larger units for industrial use, whereas the CGS system was regarded as suitable for laboratory use only.<ref name=ieeeghn>{{cite web |url = http://www.ieeeghn.org/wiki/index.php/System_of_Measurement_Units |title = System of Measurement Units |work = IEEE Global History Network |publisher = [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]] (IEEE) |accessdate = 2011-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.hydrelect.info/articles.php?lng=fr&pg=3 |title = Notions de physique – Systèmes d'unités |language = French |trans-title=Symbols used in physics - units of measure |accessdate = 2011-03-21 |publisher = Hydrelect.info}}</ref>
== Units == The base units of the MTS system are as follows: * [[length]]: [[metre]] * [[volume]]: [[cubic metre]] or [[stere]] *: 1 m<sup>3</sup> ≡ 1 st<!-- the stere applied to stacked firewood --> * [[mass]]: [[tonne]], *: 1 t = 10<sup>3</sup> kg = 1 Mg * [[time]]: [[second]] * [[force (physics)|force]]: [[sthene|sthène]], *: 1 sn = 1 t⋅m/s<sup>2</sup> = 10<sup>3</sup> [[newton (unit)|N]] = 1&nbsp;kN * [[energy]]: sthene-metre = [[kilojoule]], *: 1 sn⋅m = 1 t⋅m<sup>2</sup>/s<sup>2</sup> = 10<sup>3</sup> [[joule|J]] = 1 kJ * [[power (physics)|power]]: sthene-metre per second = [[kilowatt]], *: 1 sn⋅m/s = 1 t⋅m<sup>2</sup>/s<sup>3</sup> = 10<sup>3</sup> [[watt|W]] = 1&nbsp;kW * [[pressure]]: [[pieze|pièze]], *: 1 pz = 1 t/m⋅s<sup>2</sup> = 10<sup>3</sup> [[pascal (unit)|Pa]] = 1 kPa = 1 centibar ([[bar (unit)|cbar]])
== See also == *[[Metre–kilogram–second system of units]] (MKS) *[[Foot–pound–second system of units]] (FPS) *[[Quadrant–eleventh-gram–second system]] (QES)
